<p>
    <strong>On Staged Portraiture</strong>
</p>
<p>
    Bang.
</p>
<p>
    The patent eyelid shuts and captures the fleeting opportune as a crime.
    You, straddling; the eye in hand staring a bludgeon into the moment. Worse,
    it’s a lie, but you can always tell if it’s candid. Bang.
</p>
<p>
    You mint a token to flip in the mind-pocket with all your other odds and
    ends. It’s a payment for sacrificing a future memory; 35mm, 30 pieces of
    daguerrotype silver. Bang.
</p>
<p>
    The gold leaf floated over his face. Bang. Gilded his lower eyelids,
    squirming beneath you. Bang.
</p>
<p>
    It holds for 2 ms, just long enough to bind it to his face with a hammer.
    Bang. Let his eyes see stars in that flash.
</p>
<p>
    Stamp the moment with a middle-finger “fuck you” that fades back lemon
    sweet once it’s developed.
</p>
<p>
    Crack a glow stick in an empty room and map the spatter, get the shape but
    not the texture. Bang.
</p>
<p>
    One could kill oneself with that button. One could never find feeling in a
    lever. One snaps the shutters closed as shutters close. One hammers the
    eyelids red and blue into shape, banging fluid out flat, bang bang bang.
</p>
<p>
    The film turns black as it cures, the fluid under it and skin rising.
</p>
<p>
    Flat and enraptured, rapt and captured. Fuck, his legs kick. Bang. Stamped
    for the page, memory made.
</p>
